1. Two Layers of Structure
The quadratic iterator produces two distinct and complementary layers of information about
any payload string. These layers must be carefully distinguished.
Structural phase channels are the intrinsic outputs of the iterator’s own dynamics — the
four trajectory columns (xu, xv, xy, xz) and their associated ternary J-streams. These
emerge from the arithmetic geometry of the quadratic map itself: the dwell phases (quiet
stretches where the iterator rests within a basin) and structural transitions (ternary events
fired at basin crossings). They are not imposed — they are discovered.
Canonical symmetry channels are extrinsic positional re-framings of the payload —
running the same iterator on four procedurally transformed versions of the input bit stream:
forward, reverse, complement, and reverse complement. These are forced positional
symmetries, analogous in role to RoPE (Rotary Position Embedding) in transformer
architectures: procedural, deterministic, parameter-free impositions of geometric structure
on the encoding. Where RoPE rotates query and key vectors by position-dependent
sinusoidal angles, the canonical symmetry channels reflect and invert the bit stream by
canonical symmetry operations.
The distinction matters. Structural phase channels reveal the payload’s internal dynamics —
how the iterator moves through its attractor landscape in response to the payload.
Canonical symmetry channels reveal the payload’s positional geometry — how its
information is distributed with respect to direction, polarity, and their combination.
Together they constitute a quadratic information portrait: position and entropy structure
jointly, across both intrinsic and extrinsic dimensions.
2. Canonical Symmetry Channels — The Quad Comparator
For a payload string P with bit sequence B[], define four canonical transformations:
Forward: B[] → D*f (standard left-to-right)
Reverse: B[]↑ → D*r (right-to-left)
Complement: ~B[] → D*c (bit-flipped forward)
Reverse complement: ~B[]↑ → D*rc (bit-flipped reverse)
Each transformation is run to its canonical fixed point D* via loop iteration. No modification
to the iterator. No additional parameters. The same arithmetic at c=1.094, δ=0.002, 14dp
precision applied four times to four procedurally derived bit streams.
This is structurally identical to the four canonical representations in genomic sequence
analysis — forward strand, reverse strand, complement, and reverse complement. The
biological parallel is not coincidental: both systems are sequential binary encoders
operating on a two-symbol alphabet with inherent directionality and complementarity.
