2.2 The Four-Dimensional Fingerprint
Any string P maps to a point in four-dimensional attractor space:
fingerprint(P) = (D*f, D*r, D*c, D*rc)
The distances between channels constitute a second-order characterisation:
|D*f − D*r|: |D*f − D*c|: direction sensitivity — near-zero for palindromes
positional asymmetry — semantic opposition signal
|D*r − D*rc|: suffix asymmetry — rhyme family cohesion
|D*f − D*rc|: full diagonal — maximum structural sensitivity
The positional asymmetry |Df − Dc| is a KS-type distance — it measures how front/back-
loaded the bit distribution is, independently of bit density. The density sweep confirmed D*
is 15× more sensitive to bit arrangement than bit count, establishing that the canonical
symmetry channels are primarily positional encoders.
3. Structural Phase Channels — The Cross-Channel Entropy
Profile
The J-stream of a payload is the sequence of ternary events {-1, 0, +1} generated by the
inverse interrogation at each iterator step. Running the iterator on all four canonical
transformations produces four J-streams whose KL divergences characterise the payload’s
internal entropy structure.
