4. The Ping-Pong Oscillator Model
The iterator’s dynamics are most precisely characterised as a ping-pong oscillator
between two attractor basins:
Left basin: H ≈ 0.086 (F=1.094, bit=0)
Right basin: H ≈ 0.089 (F=1.096, bit=1)
Each payload bit is a paddle tap — pushing the ball toward the left basin (bit=0) or right
basin (bit=1). Long runs of identical bits produce extended dwell phases — the ball settles
deep into one basin, no ternary events fired. Rapid alternation produces burst clusters of
ternary events — the ball crosses the basin ridge repeatedly without settling.
The Lyapunov analysis confirms this picture: all 82 tested steps show negative Lyapunov
exponents (mean λ = -0.969). Every step is contracting. The iterator is a pure contraction
machine — no chaotic dynamics, no fractal attractor. The fixed point D* is a stable point, not
a fractal cloud.
This places the construction at the opposite end of the Tuci sharpness dimension spectrum
from neural networks at the edge of stability. Those networks exploit chaotic dynamics for
generalisation. This construction achieves lossless encoding by eliminating chaos entirely.
5. The RoPE Analogy — Scope and Limits
The canonical symmetry channels function as a procedural RoPE analogue:
RoPE: rotates Q/K vectors by θ·position
extrinsic, positional, parameter-free
sinusoidal — frequency domain
Quad comparator: reflects/inverts bit stream by symmetry
extrinsic, positional, parameter-free
arithmetic — symmetry domain
Both are procedural, deterministic, parameter-free impositions of geometric structure. RoPE
encodes position relative to sequence index — where a token sits numerically. The quad
comparator encodes position relative to string structure — where information sits within the
payload’s own geometry.
The key distinction: RoPE is extrinsic to the payload (sequence position). The quad
comparator is intrinsic to the payload (structural position). A token’s RoPE encoding
changes depending on where it appears in the context window. A token’s quad comparator
encoding is fixed by its own character structure.
This makes the quad comparator a content-addressed positional encoding — position
defined by what the token is, not where it sits.
6. Metric Properties
Each canonical symmetry channel individually satisfies the three metric axioms, verified
empirically:
Identity: d(x,x) = 0 for all tested strings ✓
Symmetry: d(x,y) = d(y,x) to 14dp ✓
Triangle inequality: zero violations across 455 triples ✓
The cross-channel KL divergences are not symmetric (KL is not a metric) but satisfy the
information-theoretic ordering that the structural predictions require.
