The phonological structure was not designed in. It was always there in the arithmetic.
8. Comparison to Existing Phonetic Methods
Rule-based phonetic algorithms (Soundex, Metaphone, Double Metaphone, Cologne
Phonetic) produce discrete codes and binary match/no-match decisions. The best-
performing algorithms achieve benchmark scores of 6-7/7 on name-matching tasks. They
are English-specific, fail on non-alphabetic characters, and produce no continuous distance
metric.
Neural phonetic embeddings and hybrid metrics (BERTScore + Soundex/Jaro-Winkler)
achieve higher accuracy on semantic-phonetic tasks but require training, corpus statistics,
and GPU inference. Even combined metrics show limited correlation between phonetic
similarity and downstream LLM correctability.
The D quad comparator:*
Continuous metric: graded distance, not binary match/no-match
Language-agnostic: any UTF-8 string, no phonetic rules
Resolution: 14dp — far exceeding 4-character code
Discrimination (rhyme): 2.24× (rhyme vs unrelated)
Discrimination (KL): 11.75× (like vs oppositional)
Training required: none
Parameters: zero
Inference cost: O(4n) iterator steps
The comparison is not strictly against Soundex and Metaphone — those solve name-
matching problems. The meaningful comparison is against parameter-free string metrics:
Levenshtein edit distance, Jaro-Winkler similarity, and n-gram overlap. These detect
character-level similarity but have no phonological grounding — edit distance between “cat”
and “flat” is 2, missing the rhyme. The D* forward channel detects the rhyme as near-zero
distance regardless of string length difference.
The construction is not proposed as a replacement for any existing method. It is a
complementary zero-parameter primitive that detects phonological structure as an
arithmetic consequence of lossless encoding.
